� General Information
Aggregate Adaptation module for implementation of generic FUSL package to SIMOS12.
� Application Conditions
Initialisation: at reset:
EFPPWM_I = 0
EFPPWM_I_AD = 0
EFPPWM_MIN_AD = 0
FUP_EFP_STOP_H = 0
FUP_EFP_STOP_L = 0
FUP_EFP_ST_H = 0
FUP_EFP_ST_L = 0
T_EFP_MEM_H = 0
T_EFP_MEM_L = 0
calculate complete formular section, additionally
Activation: always
Deactivation: never
Recurrence: IF LV_ST_END == 1
THEN SEG
ELSE 10ms
ENDIF
� Function Description
FUP_H = FUP
FUP_L_SAE = (FUP_EFP_MES - AMP) *(0.1 kPa/hPa)
FUP_REL_SAE = (FUP_EFP_MES - MAP) *(0.1 kPa/hPa)
LV_REFU_ACT = LV_FFFI_ACT
RHO_FUEL = IP_RHO_FUEL( TFU_HPP )
TFU_HPP_MES = 0 %[�C]
V_FUP_EFP_MV = VP_FUP_EFP_MES
VFF_HPP = MAX (0; (MFF_SP_EFP_CTL) * 60 / ( RHO_FUEL * T_SEG_AV ))
R_VCV = C_R_VCV_NORM * (1 +
((TFPA - 20�C) * C_FAC_R_TFPA_VCV_SLOP_NORM [1/K])
)

FUSL, Fuel temperature
43.3.3.1 Calculation and correction of the fuel temperature at injector head
TFU_COR_STAT_PUC_PU is the basic value of the fuel temperature. It is calculated according the three operat-
ing states "normal", "pull fuel cut off" and "pull".
This value has to be corrected to compensate the in?uence of the "vehicle speed", "coolant temperature",
"engine warm-up (oil temperature)" and "ignition angle".
The correction is done by adding the accordingly correction value which is extracted from a map.
If an TFU sensor is available TFU is calculated of the sensor value, otherwise the modelled TFU is used.

43.3.3.1.1.1.3 Calculation of the basic fuel temperature via the hot- and cold map
Here the basic value of the fuel temperature in static operating state is determined. If the values of the map
for cold engine and the map for hot engine are equal, the value from the cold map is used.
Via this algorithm a linear interpolation, depending on the ambient air temperature (TAM), between the hot-
and cold-map is performed.
The basis for TFU_STAT is the value of the cold-map.
To this value the difference of the hot- and cold-map, which is manipulated before by a TAM depending factor,
is added.

43.3.3.1.1.1.8 Determination of usage of Static-, PU- or PUC-Algorithm
Normally the calculation over the hot- and cold-map is used (fc_STAT).
If a PU-Phase occurs (LV_PU == 1) the actual values of engine speed (N_32) and the fuel temperature in static
state, PUC or PU (TFU_COR_STAT_PUC_PU_PREV_FIL) are stored by the subfunction "SAVE_PUC". The Calcu-
lation over the hot- and cold-map is still used (fc_STAT). The aim is only to store the values for a following
PUC-Phase.
If a PUC-Phase occurs (LV_PUC == 1) the calculation via the PUC-map is used (fc_PUC). The need values for
the calculation were stored at the entering of a former PU-Phase or directly at entering the PUC-Phase, if no
PU-Phase occurred before.
The calculation over the PUC-Map stays active as long as TQ_AV <C_TQ_AV_TFU_PU_COR even if LV_PUC ==
0. This is implemented to cover part load phases during a PUC-Phase which are caused by gear shifting.
The calculation via the PU-map (fc_PU) is only used if the PU-phase follows directly after a PUC-phase and TQ_
AV >C_TQ_AV_TFU_PU_COR. The need values for the calculation of the PU-Phase are stored at the entering
of the PU-Phase by the subfunction SAVE_PU.

43.3.3.1.3.1 Calculation of TFU-Correction during start phase
Calc.-TFU >TCO (before start)
If, before start, Calc.-TFU>TCO then TFU = TCO till engine start.
At and after ?nished engine start (LV_ST_END == 1) TFU is ramped from TCO to the Calc.-TFU with the increment
of C_TFU_COR_INC. If TFU has reached the Calc.-TFU, TFU is always the Calc.-TFU.
Calc.-TFU <TCO (before start)
If, before start, Calc.-TFU<TCO then TFU = Calc.-TFU.
Deactivatin of the function after start phase
C_T_TFU_CLC_ST_END determines at which time after start the start correction is disabled and the TFU value
is the calculated TFU value (without any ramping).
Thereby it is avoided that the start correction function can in?uence the "normal" calculation of the TFU.
If C_T_TFU_CLC_ST_END == 0, the start correction function is completely disabled and TFU is always the calcu-
lated value.

43.3.3.1.4.1 Calculation of TFU-Correction during idle speed phase
The TFU correction during idle speed phase is done via an offset.
The value of the offset is ramped-in if the condition of the idle speed correction is ful?lled and the delay time
C_TFU_IS_OFS_DLY has elapsed.
The value is limited to an de?ned max. value.
If the conditions are not ful?lled anymore and the delay time for the ramp out C_TFU_IS_OFS_RAMP_OUT_DLY
has elapsed, the offset value is ramped-out till the corrected TFU value has reached the "normal" modeled TFU
value again.

� Import actions:
ACTION_INFR_GetVFupSens(OUT <PRM_VP_FUP_RAW>)
� General Information
Within this module the raw signal voltage of high pressure sensor - which is located in the fuel rail - is acquired,
averaged, converted and ?ltered. Processed pressure value is provided as main module output.
Raw sensor voltage is provided by Import Action ?ACTION_INFR_GetVFupSens?.
Two alternating pairs of buffers are used for synchronisation of signal acquisition at 1ms recurrence, and signal
processing at 10 ms recurrence (LV_ST_END = 0) / segment recurrence (LV_ST_END = 1), respectively. Thus
read/write inconsistencies due to asynchronous task execution are prevented.

43.6.2.2.3 Signal ?ltering and limphome reaction
In case of an error inside the sensor voltage and during debouncing of the sensor voltage error, fuel pressure
setpoint FUP_SP is used. After fuel pressure error debouncing and request of limp home due to error detec-
tion, a replacement value for fuel pressure in rail is applied. It is based on pressure value in low pressure fuel
system caused by fuel pressure decrease dependent to MFF_SP_FUP_CTL. An additional constant offset can
be applied to account for typical pressure difference between mounting location of low pressure sensor and
within fuel rail.
Finally PT1 low-pass ?ltering is applied to measured fuel pressure.

� General Information
Due to the fact that the fuel pressure sensor for the high pressure circuit has a constant error independent
on the measured pressure the absolute error is highest at low measured fuel pressure level. The fuel pressure
in the low pressure circuit has nearly the same as the high pressure in the fuel rail. Only the pressure loss
because of the high pressure pump is different. This leads to the fact that the fuel pressure sensor value in
the high pressure circuit can be adapted with the value of the low pressure circuit fuel pressure sensor under
certain conditions.
In case of no fuel pressure sensor failure of the low pressure circuit and the high pressure circuit an adaptation
is applied. This is only possible if the coolant temperature value is within speci?ed limits and the measured fuel
pressure sensor value is below a certain limit. This is done because of the possibility of high pressure in the
fuel rail, where no adaptation is possible.
If all this conditions are ful?lled the fuel pressure value of the low fuel pressure sensor is taken as reference
value when the engine starts turning. This is done because of the fuel pressure build up time for the low
pressure circuit. If no reference value is possible the last value will be taken out of the permanent memory.
If a certain fuel pressure value is reached the adaptation value is skipped and will be removed by a gradient
limitation.
The limp home value of the fuel pressure is also created in this function. Depending on the error ?ag of the
fuel pressure sensor a substitute will be taken.
In case of checksum error of the EEPROM or for an brand new ECU all values of the MAP ID_FUP_MIN_AD are
set to 0 hPA.

Processed pressure value is provided as main module output.
Raw sensor voltage is provided by Import Action ?ACTION_INFR_GetVFupEfpSens?. Two alternating pairs of
buffers are used for synchronization of signal acquisition at 1ms recurrence, and signal processing at 10 ms re-
currence (LV_ST_END = 0) / segment recurrence (LV_ST_END = 1), respectively. Thus read/write inconsistencies
due to asynchronous task execution are prevented.

PRM_SRV_31_ROUTINE_STATE = C0h
else(b)
// short trip not started
PRM_SRV_31_ROUTINE_STATE = 00h
end if(b)
end if(a)
STATE_EFP_EXT_REQ = PRM_SRV_31_ROUTINE_STATE;
End ACTION

� General Information
The control algorithm can be used for all kind of ?ow controlled pump. This function is the interface of the fuel
pressure acquisition and the fuel pressure setpoint calculation to the fuel pump control.
It calculates basically a requested fuel mass to be delivered into the fuel rail by the HP pump. This calculation
is based on the fuel pressure setpoint, measured fuel pressure, the fuel mass ?ow setpoint and the feedback
of the pump interface, which is the fuel mass delivered by the pump. Additionally there is the input fuel
temperature, which is needed to correct the calculation of the fuel mass in the rail.

43.14.2.1.2.1 Calculation of P controller part
Out of the fuel pressure deviation related to the used fuel pressure the p-control value is calculated. This value
can be modi?ed by the weighting factor given by the map. Out of this calculated p-control fuel pressure value
a p-control fuel mass must be chosen. This is done by the second map. Additionally it can be necessary to
add more fuel due to avoid fuel pressure decrease at fast load change requested by fast pedal activation. This
is done by an additional map.

� General Information
Working of the high pressure system :
The module fuel pump control is basically the interface from the output of fuel pressure control to the actual
type of the fuel pump. Figure 1 below shows the fuel system from the tank (canister) to the injectors. The
low pressure pump is delivering fuel to the high pressure single piston pump at a controlled pressure. For
steady conditions with no pressure changes the amount of fuel delivered to the rail is the same as the injected
amount of fuel into the combustion chamber.
Figure 43.15.1: Fuel system layout

FUSL, Fuel pressure actuator control
Reference angle de?nition for working of the Volume control valve (VCV) :
The reference point for the pump is the TDC of the plunger of the pump for the calculation of fuel mass
delivery. Since the pump is mounted on the camshaft, this point is camshaft related, but the whole calculation
for the VCV control is crankshaft angle based. Therefore the transfer between these two systems has to be
done via a so called reference angle. Hence this angle includes the difference of the TDC of the plunger of
the pump to the corresponding TDC of the engine cylinders on the crankshaft (for example, the reference
angles of a 4 cylinder engine with engine cylinder TDC?s and pump TDC?s on same angles are 180� CRK, 360�
CRK, 540� CRK and 720� CRK). The reference angle calculation also includes IVVT in?uences and mounting
in?uences. The ?gure 2 below shows the relation of the reference angle with respect to the pump TDC.
Figure 43.15.2: Reference angle position w.r.t. piston position of the pump
Basic working principle of the VCV :
The functional principle of the single piston pump is described below. The lobe, which is driving the plunger
of the pump is directly connected to the camshaft. The plunger movement depends on the architecture of
the pump and the lobe pro?le. Depending on this movement the amount of fuel delivered can be calculated.
There is a suction stroke and a pressure (delivery) stroke.
The ?gure 3 below shows the signals for operating the single cylinder pump. It can be seen that the control
valve has to be closed within the suction stroke to ensure a fully closed valve at the beginning of the pressure
stroke from BDC if 100% delivery is to be given to the rail. Depending on the amount (0% to 100%) of delivery
required, the closing angle of the VCV is calculated. The closing and opening commands are depending on
the different pump types.
There are two types of VCV?s,
1. Currentless open VCV (Figure 3)
In case of no applied current to the solenoid of the VCV, the valve is open. During suction stroke, the fuel enters
the pump chamber and the amount of fuel that will be delivered into the rail is decided based on the crank
angle at which the valve is closed, i.e. current is stopped.
We can see from the below ?gure that, ANG_CUR_ON is the angle at which current feed of the valve is started
and the closing of the valve is started and the ANG_CUR_OFF is the angle at which current feed of the valve is

deactivated. We see that the valve remains closed even after current is stopped, this is due to the pressure of
the compressed fuel in the pump chamber which acts against the spring force in the VCV and keeps the valve
closed just before delivery.
2. Currentless close VCV (Figure 4)
In case of no applied current to the solenoid of the VCV, the valve is closed. During suction stroke, the current is
given to the valve to open and the fuel enters the pump chamber and the amount of fuel that will be delivered
into the rail is decided based on the crank angle at which the valve is closed, i.e. current is stopped.
We can see from the below ?gure that, ANG_CUR_ON is the angle at which current feed of the valve is started
and the ANG_CUR_OFF is the angle at which the current feed of the valve is deactivated and the closing of the
valve is started. We see that the valve closes quicker than currentless open VCV after current is stopped, this
is due to the pressure of the compressed fuel in the pump chamber acting with the spring force in the VCV to
close the valve.

The VCV control calculations are done in time based mode until the engine is synchronised and the calcula-
tions are done in segment based mode after the engine is synchronised.
Current pro?le of VCV :
The VCV is operated by high side and low side switches. Regardless of currentless open or currentless close
VCV, the current pro?le is the same. For detalied representation of the current pro?le of the VCV please refer
to the ?Requirements to infrastructure? module of FUSL aggregate. For better understanding of this module,
the basic currrent pro?le is explained below.
The current pro?le during VCV actuation consists of four phases,
1. Pull-in phase ? During this phase, the maximum height of the current is reached (100% PWM is applied). The
VCV is completely open by end of this stage if its a currentless closed VCV and completely closed by end of
this stage if its a currentless open VCV.
2. Hold phase ? During this phase, a variable current is obtained (between 0% and 100% PWM applied) by
closing and opening the high side switch of the VCV in different patterns based on the PWM signal input. The
low side switch is closed during this phase. All phases after this are mainly done to remove the inductivity
effect in the VCV due to the application of high voltage.

3. Free wheeling phase ? During this phase, current is reduced through a free wheeling diode by keeping the
high side switch open and low side switch closed.
4. Clamping phase ? During this phase, the remaining residual curent is reduced to zero through clamping
diodes by keeping both the high side switch and low side switch open.

VCV control states :
The pump has speci?c operating states, which are mentioned in the state diagram for STATE_VCV below.
These states depend on the requested fuel mass for the fuel rail, which has to be delivered by the pump. As
we can see from the ?gure 6 below, that before engine synchronisation, only the MFP_START phase can be
requested and only after synchronisation, other state transitions can be performed.
VCV_OPEN
In the state ?VCV_OPEN? no fuel should be delivered to the fuel rail. The variable LV_INH_VCV is set to 1. The
VCV closing angle is set to zero to ensure zero delivery. In this state, the VCV is open and the BSW does not
execute any closing command to the solenoid of VCV. When the engine is not running, the VCV_OPEN state is
set.
MFP_START
This state is requested whenever the engine is cranked and this state is retained until the engine is synchro-
nized and the fuel pressure reaches the desired setpoint. This state is initiated to achieve faster fuel pressure
increase in the fuel rail to enable combustion. In order to have quick pressure increase, a continuous current
is supplied to the VCV to have a constant fuel delivery from the pump. To see the current pro?le of the VCV at
start phase, please refer to the ?Requirements to infrastructure? module of FUSL aggregate.
MFP_MAX

The pump can only deliver a certain amount of fuel per stroke. The maximum deliverable fuel mass into the
rail is MFP_MAX. In the state MFP_MAX, the full pumping performance of the pump is requested. Therefore the
maximum pump performance is 100% and the maximum VCV closing angle is applied.
MFP_CTL
The state ?MFP_CTL? is the only state where controlled (requested) fuel mass can be delivered by the pump. In
this state, the required pump performance is calculated using MFP_MAX and MFP_REQ. With the help of the
pump performance, the VCV closing angle is determined.
VCV_TEST
The state ?VCV_TEST? is basically for testing purposes. In the test mode VCV_TEST, the pump performanceis
adjusted manually by a calibration. If the value of this variable is 0, then the bit LV_INH_VCV is set to 1, when
this happens the BSW does not execute any closing command to the solenoid of VCV.

43.15.1.1 Initialization at Reset
Initialization at ECU reset of all calculated variables is done in this section.
At every engine stop and or at ECU reset, the time to remain in VCV start phase is limited by calibration (C_T_
VCV_MFP_START). Until the engine has exited the start phase, the VCV control will not switch to control phase,
but in order to ensure that the current (continuous) feed is not too long which will result in heating of the VCV,
this calibration can be used.
In case of multi-pump con?guration, the number of pumps mounted on the engine can be set through a
calibration (C_PUMP_NR).
Each pump can be disabled thorugh a calibration (C_DI_MOD). When the disable mode is active, then the
communication from the ASW to IO (BSW) is stopped.

In case of multi-pump con?guration, the number of pumps mounted on the engine can be set through a
calibration (C_PUMP_NR).

communication from the ASW to IO (BSW) is stopped. When the DIV is operational through ATIC 113 (High

43.15.2 Calculation Sequence
As long as the Engine is not synchronized, there is no segment based calculation for the VCV control, instead
the calculation is time based (10 ms).
We see in the below ?gure that, as long as Engine is locked (for example via Immobilizer) or Engine is in power
latch phase or Engine is running without synchronization or Engine is stopped or if the Engine has not yet
exited the start phase , the subsystems are triggered every 10ms.

43.15.2.1.1.1 Manual setting of VCV current control parameters via application tool (overview)
Depending on CLF_CUR_CTL_MOD_VCV and CLF_CUR_CTL_MOD_VCV_TEST the related current control pa-
rameters are calculated in a different way for each control phase.
CLF_CUR_CTL_MOD_VCV de?nes which phase of the VCV control pulse is executed in closed or open loop
current control mode.
Current control phases:
bit 0: PEAK
bit 1: CTL_0 (= pick-up = hold_0)
bit 2: CTL_1 (= hold_1)
bit 3: DEACC_PEAK
bit 4: DEACC (_hold)
bit 5: ST (= start)
Current control modes:
? bit x is set: closed loop current control mode is executed for related phase
? bit x is reset: open loop current control mode is executed for related phase
CLF_CUR_CTL_MOD_VCV_TEST de?nes which test mode for each VCV control pulse phase is executed in case
of closed loop current control mode is enabled:
?

bit x is set: closed loop current control mode is executed for related phase
? bit x is reset: open loop current control mode is executed for related phase
CLF_CUR_CTL_MOD_VCV_TEST de?nes which test mode for each VCV control pulse phase is executed in case
of closed loop current control mode is enabled:
? bit x is set: IP_PWM_CUR_VCV_REQ in combination with C_CUR_VCV_... is considered to adjust the related
closed loop current control phase
? bit x is reset: C_PWM_VCV_... is considered to adjust the related closed loop current control phase

43.15.2.1.2.1.1.2 Pump limits calculation with Small-quantity regulation
The maximum physically possible quantitiy per stroke that can be delivered by the pump is calibrated through
C_MFP_MAX. However, this maximum quantity is affected by several factors, namely, fuel temperature, the
injected fuel mass, the fuel pressure in the rail and the engine speed and as a result these in?uences are given
by the maps as factors which decide the ?nal maximum quantity at any particular time of operation.
These factors collectively affect the overall delivery ef?cieny of the pump and can be called as ef?ciency
factors.
IP_FAC_FUEL_PUMP_EFF_TFU_N gives the dependancy of fuel temperature in the pump and engine speed.
This factor reduces at higher fuel temperatures, since at high temperatures the pump tolerances increase
along with decrease in fuel density causing lower delivery rates due to leakages.
IP_FAC_FUEL_PUMP_EFF_MFF_SP_N gives the dependancy of mass fuel ?ow set point for fuel pressure control
and engine speed. This factor was included to accomidate the dead volume in?uence of the pump.However,
this calibration need not be used anymore for dead volume effects, since the dead volume in?uence is now
covered through MFP_OFS.
IP_FAC_FUEL_PUMP_EFF_FUP_N gives the dependancy of fuel pressure setpoint and engine speed. This factor
is usually high at lower speeds and low at higher engine speeds. It is basicially introduced to compensate for
engine load. As the fuel pressure in the rail is higher with higher engine loads, the work done by the pump to
overcome this pressure and deliver the fuel into the rail is higher.
The pump chamber dead volume in?uence is covered under two maps.
IP_MFP_OFS gives the dead-volume in?uence based on fuel pressure and engine speed. The dead volume

varies with engine speed and fuel quantitiy inside the pump chamber. The dead volume in?uence at lower
engine speed with lower quantitiy is lower (since, the quanitity is low and the fuel compression is easier) and
the same in?uence is higher at higher engine speed with higher quantity (since, the quantity is high and the
fuel compression requires more work from the pump).
Also, change in temperature changes the fuel density and hence the quantitiy. So, in order to consider this
in?uence based on temperature, a calibration map is present (IP_MFP_OFS_TFU_ADD).
Since the ratio of engine cylinder to pump stroke affects the mass fuel delivered every stroke, a calibratable
factor (C_FAC_FUEL_PUMP_CTL) can be used to consider this effect for calculation of fuel mass requested from
the pump by the fuel pressure control.

43.15.2.1.2.1.1.2.1 Small-quantity regulation
A small-quantity is recognized if the fuel mass requested by the controller is less than a certain calibrated
threshold (C_MFP_REQ_MIN) and is de-recognized if the fuel mass request is higher than calibated threshold
(C_MFP_REQ_MAX).
The small-quantity regulation can be activated manually through a switch (LC_MFP_REQ_L_ACT). This is pro-
vided in case the calibrations above are not present and, small quantity should not be recognized by mistake.
This is mainly used during development phases.
Depending on whether the small-quantity was delivered in the previous recurrence or not, the activation for
delivery of small-quantity for the current recurrence is decided using a switch. Every second delivery is deac-
tivated, in case small-quantity ?ag is active. This working is explained below,
if the current requested quantity is lower than C_MFP_REQ_MIN, then this quantity is not considered for the
fuel mass calculation, but if the quantity of the previous recurrence was also not considered (i.e. it was less
than C_MFP_REQ_MIN), then the current quantity + the previous quantity will be considered for fuel mass
calculation.
If the current requested quantity is higher than C_MFP_REQ_MAX, then, this quantitiy is delivered in the current
recurrence.

FUSL, Fuel pressure actuator control
The VCV runs in a time based operating mode untill the engine is synchronized and VCV control in crank
based mode is initiated only after the engine is synchronized and regardless of the ignition key status.
The VCV control in start phase is triggered when,
1. Engine is running, but not synchronized
2. Start pulse is still applied to the VCV (T_VCV_MFP_START is still running), i.e. a constant current is applied to
the VCV during start phase for a calibrated time duration.
The VCV control in open phase is triggered when,
1. No high pressure start is requested
2. Engine has not exited the start phase but synchronized
3. Limp home mode due to errors in fuel supply system is active
4. a request by external functionality is set
5. Start pulse is not applied to the VCV (T_VCV_MFP_START is zero)
6. No fuel mass is requested from fuel pressure control and from pump delivery
7. Fuel pressure difference (setpoint ? actual value) is below a calibrated threshold (C_FUP_DIF_VCV_OPEN_
THD).
The VCV is fully open in the open phase. No current is given to it in case of currentless open VCV and 100%
current is given to it in case of currentless close VCV.
The VCV control in maximum delivery phase is triggered when,
1. Fuel mass requested from fuel pressure control exceeds the maximum delivery quantity and fuel pressure
control deviation is positive
2. High pressure start is requested before engine has exited the start phase
The engine has to be synchronized for maximum delivery phase to be triggered.
The closed loop control for fuel pressure is inactive during the maximum delivery phase. The I controller is
frozen in order to avoid winding up error when the fuel pressure control is active again.
The VCV control in request control phase is triggered when,
1. When VCV control is not in open phase
2. When VCV control is not in maximum delivery phase
The engine has to be synchronized for request control phase to be triggered.
The VCV control in test phase is triggered when,
1. When the calibration LC_PUMP_VOL_VCV_MAN is set
2. Engine is no longer in start phase
The engine has to be synchronized for test phase to be triggered.

43.15.2.1.2.2.3.1.1 Calculation of VCV soft landing control
To minimize noise of VCV actuation and VCV wear, a lower current is applied to VCV during certain conditions
(especially below engine speeds of 1000 rpm). This function as a whole is called as soft landing (SL) function
of the VCV.
The SL application is based on the working points of the VCV based on the battery voltage (VB) and temper-
ature of the VCV (given in terms of resistance of the VCV, R_VCV). In order to cover component tolerances an
adaptation for SL is done based on fuel pressure analysis. The adaptation is also re- learnt if the working points
(VB, R_VCV) at which the adaptation was performed have shifted by calibrated thresholds.
Soft landing current pro?le :
File: AE904B01.00D
12027Project: VW SIMOS 18.1 EA888 Document key: 10213413 SPE 000 DE
Baseline: SC8L50Y0 Copyright Continental AG

Copyright �Continental AG. Transmittal, reproduction, dissemination and/or editing of this document as well as utilisation of its contents and communication thereof to others without
expressed authorisation are prohibited. Offenders will be held liable for payment of damages. All rights created by patent grant or registration of a utility model or design patent are reserved.
FUSL, Fuel pressure actuator control
In order to minimize noise of VCV actuation and VCV wear, the VCV current pro?le is modi?ed in order to
reduce the peak current height in the pull-in phase and have an extended hold phase (pwm based).
There is another additional stage in the SL current pro?le called pick-up phase. This is introduced in order to
identify the right current height to be applied during the adaptation for the pull-in phase.
The adaptation is a two step process. First, the pick-up adaptation is done and next the pull-in adaptation is
done.
Pick-up adaptation ? During pick-up adaptation, the pull-in value is not changed. The adaptation is done con-
tinuously in a step wise manner, by decreasing the current in a pre-calculated way untill the current is so less,
that the VCV cannot be closed anymore. This is known, when we see a pressure drop in the system, as the
VCV is not closed completely and this leads to a pressure drop in the system due to some of the pressurized
fuel returning to the low pressure side due to a still open VCV. Then, the last applied value added by an offset
is freezed as the adapted value of the pick-up phase of the VCV.
Pull-adaptation ? During pull-in adaptation, the pick-up adaptation is already completed. Based on the pick-up
adaptation, the pull-in adaptation is freezed. The pull-in adaptation is done similar to the pick-up adaptation as
explained above.

43.15.2.1.2.2.3.1.1.1.1.1 Main authorizations for activation of VCV soft landing
Main authorizations for VCV soft landing are dependent to environmental conditions, namely,
1. After start time ? only after a calibratable after start time of C_T_AST_VCV_SL_MIN is passed, SL is enabled.
This is done to ensure that the VCV control has stabilized after start.
2. Battery voltage ? For SL to be applied, suf?cient battery voltage needs to be ensured, this is done by
checking it against a calibratable threshold C_VB_VCV_SL_MIN. The current duration is usually extended for
the SL operation of the VCV and if the battery voltage is too low, the VCV actuation pulse would become too
long for one pump period.
3. Coolant temperature ? The coolant temperature has the strongest in?uence on the VCV temperature. So, in
order to avoid SL in case of higher temperatures, the TCO is checked whether its in between the calibrated min-
imum and maximum temperature thresholds of C_TCO_VCV_SL_MIN and C_TCO_VCV_SL_MAX respectively.
For VCV close SL, there are additional conditions which decide the initiation of SL, namely,
1. Engine speed ? SL can only be applied upto particular range of engine speed, because with increased engine
speed, the pump period become too short for applying extended VCV actuation pulses during SL.
So, as long as the engine speed is below the calibrated threshold C_N_VCV_CLOSE_SL_HYS_MIN and not above
the calibrated threshold C_N_VCV_CLOSE_SL_HYS_MAX, SL is authorized.
2. Fuel pressure deviation ? SL can be active only if it does not interfere with the fuel pressure control.

So, as long as the engine speed is below the calibrated threshold C_N_VCV_CLOSE_SL_HYS_MIN and not above
the calibrated threshold C_N_VCV_CLOSE_SL_HYS_MAX, SL is authorized.
2. Fuel pressure deviation ? SL can be active only if it does not interfere with the fuel pressure control. In order
to ensure that SL is not active in case of high fuel pressure deviations, a hysteresis function is built. So, as long
as the fuel pressure deviation is below the calibrated threshold C_FUP_DIF_VCV_CLOSE_SL_HYS_MIN and not
above the calibrated threshold C_FUP_DIF_VCV_CLOSE_SL_HYS_MAX, SL is authorized.

FUSL, Fuel pressure actuator control
If the engine speed and fuel pressure deviation are within the respective thresholds, then a calibrated waiting
time C_T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_SL_AUTH has to be passed, in order to activate SL for VCV closing. This is to ensure
that the system is stable before initiating SL.
SL for VCV opening activates the deceleration pulse. Similar to SL for VCV closing, there are engine speed and
fuel pressure deviation dependencies for activating SL for VCV opening and are explained below,
1. Engine speed ? As long as the engine speed is below the calibrated threshold C_N_VCV_OPEN_SL_HYS_MIN
and not above the calibrated threshold C_N_VCV_OPEN_SL_HYS_MAX, SL for VCV opening is authorised.
2. Fuel pressure deviation ? As long as the fuel pressure deviation is below the calibrated threshold C_FUP_
DIF_VCV_OPEN_SL_HYS_MIN and not above the calibrated threshold C_FUP_DIF_VCV_OPEN_SL_HYS_MAX, SL
for VCV opening is authorised.
3. State of SL for VCV closing ? In addition to above two parameters, the SL for VCV opening depends on the
state of SL for VCV closing. SL for VCV opening is usually only active, if the SL adaptation for VCV closing is
?nished.
The difference in the hysteresis thresholds between SL for VCV closing and SL for VCV opening is, that the
thresholds for VCV opening are more narrower that for VCV closing.
Similar to SL for VCV closing, a calibrated waiting time C_T_DLY_VCV_OPEN_SL_AUTH has to be passed, in order
to activate SL for VCV opening. This is to ensure that the system is stable before initiating SL.
After the authorisation is given to activate VCV SL for closing, the fuel pressure deviation is monitored in order
to ensure that SL operation does not cause un-wanted pressure drops in the system when its active.
Two counters are operated parallely depending on the fuel pressure deviation observed.
In case the fuel pressure drops are witihin limits (lv_fup_dif_hys_min) when SL is active, then CTR_FUP_DIF_VCV_
CLOSE_SL_AUTH is incremented.
In case the fuel pressure drops are more than the allowed limits (lv_fup_dif_hys_min) when SL is active, then
CTR_FUP_DIF_HYS_MAX_AUTH is incremented.
As long as the fuel pressure drop is within limits, i.e. CTR_FUP_DIF_VCV_CLOSE_SL_AUTH is greater than the
calibratable threshold C_CTR_FUP_DIF_VCV_SL_AUTH_MAX, then the counter CTR_FUP_DIF_HYS_MAX_AUTH
is reset.
In case the fuel pressure drop is beyond the limits, the counter CTR_FUP_DIF_HYS_MAX_AUTH is incremented
and triggers SL adaptation reset which is described in the next subsystem.

43.15.2.1.2.2.3.1.1.1.1.2 Control of adaptations for soft landing during VCV closing
VCV current adaptation during VCV closing can be activated in steady-state conditions. Essential parameters
(working points) affecting VCV actuation are compared between values stored during last adaptation against
current ones. In case of a too high deviation, a reset of adaptation or request for re-adaptation is set.
The adaptation authorisation for VCV closing SL depends on several conditions,
1. The main authorisation for VCV closing SL should be active
2. The engine should be in idle speed state and the engine speed to be within the calibratable threshold of
C_N_MAX_VCV_SL_AD_AUTH
3. The fuel pressure setpoint gradient to be within the calibratable threshold of C_FUP_SP_GRD_VCV_SL_AD_
AUTH
4. The fuel pressure deviation to be within the calibratable threshold of C_FUP_DIF_VCV_SL_AD_AUTH
If the above conditions are met, then a calibrated waiting time C_T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_SL_AD_AUTH has to be
passed, in order to activate SL adaptation for VCV closing. This is to ensure that the system is stable before
initiating SL adaptation.
The adaptation reset for VCV closing SL is active depending on several conditions,
1. Either the PWM or T_DUR adaptation should be in progress or Adaptation should have already been com-
pleted and applied. These states are indicated from STATE_VCV_CLOSE_SL.
2. The change in Battery voltage at the start of adaptation (stored) with respect to the current battery voltage
is compared against calibrated thresholds. These thresholds are different depending on whether an adapta-
tion is currently active or not. If currently an adaptation is active, then C_VB_DIF_MAX_CLOSE_SL_RST_AD is
considered and if adaptation is not active, then C_VB_DIF_MAX_CLOSE_SL_RST is considered.
3. The change in resistance of VCV at the start of adaptation (stored) with respect to the current VCV resis-
tance is compared against calibrated thresholds. These thresholds are different depending on whether an
adaptation is currently active or not. If currently an adaptation is active, then C_R_DIF_MAX_CLOSE_SL_RST_AD
is considered and if adaptation is not active, then C_R_DIF_MAX_CLOSE_SL_RST is considered.
4. The counter CTR_FUP_DIF_HYS_MAX_AUTH is greater than calibrated threshold C_CTR_FUP_DIF_HYS_MAX_
AUTH. As explained in the previous subsystem, if there are existing pressure drops even after adaptation, then
it indicates a wrong adaptation.
5. In order to also consider the periodically new adaptation after a de?nite time interval, the calibatable time
threshold C_T_MAX_VCV_CLOSE_SL_AD_VLD is considered.
As long as the working points, VB (Battery voltage) and R_VCV (VCV resistance) have not deviated much, then
the current learnt adaptation is suf?cient to be used. A new adaptation is requested if VB and R_VCV have
changed when compared to their last stored values when the previous adaptation was done.
Change in VB is compared against the calibratable threshold C_VB_DIF_MAX_VCV_CLOSE_SL_REQ and
Change in R_VCV is compared against the calibratable threshold C_R_DIF_MAX_VCV_CLOSE_SL_REQ.

43.15.2.1.2.2.3.1.1.1.2 Status of soft landing during VCV closing
Status of soft landing during VCV closing consists of following states:
0 - no soft landing during VCV closing active
1 - soft landing during VCV closing active with default parameters
2 - adaptation of duty-cycle for VCV holding phase
3 - adaptation of pull-in time for VCV peak (pull-in) phase

4 - adapted soft landing during VCV closing active
The adaptation for VCV closing SL is completed if the counter CTR_VCV_CLOSE_SL_AD is greater than the cal-
ibrated counter thresholds for PWM adaptation (C_CTR_MAX_VCV_CLOSE_SL_AD_PWM) or T_DUR adaptation
(C_CTR_MAX_VCV_CLOSE_SL_AD_T_DUR).
The adaptation for VCV closing SL is ?on hold?, i.e. a condition favourable to initiate an adaptation is in anticipa-
tion when,
1. VCV close SL is authorized
2. Engine is in idle speed
3. Engine speed is less than the calibrated threshold C_N_MAX_VCV_SL_AD_AUTH
4. The last adaptation learning process has not yet ended
5. Fuel pressure is less than the calibrated threshold C_FUP_MAX_VCV_SL_AD_AUTH
The state ?AD_PWM? represents pick-up adaptation under progress. The pick-up adaptation is completed when
the counter crosses the calibrated threshold, C_CTR_MAX_VCV_CLOSE_SL_AD_PWM.
The state ?AD_T_DUR? represents pull-in adaptation under progress. The pull-in adaptation is completed when
the counter crosses the calibrated threshold, C_CTR_MAX_VCV_CLOSE_SL_AD_T_DUR.
The state switch between ?AD_PWM? and ?AD_T_DUR? is determined based on the comparison of the adaptation
counter value and calibrated counter thresholds of the repsective states.

43.15.2.1.2.2.3.1.1.1.3 Auxiliary variables for soft landing adaption during VCV closing
In auxiliary part, the essential parameters affecting VCV actuation are stored at beginning of adaptation and at
end of adaptation.
If the current adaptation is completed, and there is an adaptation request, then the current PWM and T_DUR
adaptation values are offset using the calibrated thresholds C_PWM_AD_OFS_VCV_CLOSE_SL_REQ and C_T_
DUR_AD_OFS_VCV_CLOSE_SL_REQ respectively. This is done as it is assumed that as long as the shift of the
working points affecting the adaptation are within the ?adaptation request? calibration range, then it is safe
enough for the application of the (same) already learnt adaptation values through only correction of an offset.
This is done to avoid un-necessary triggering of adaptation process.
However, a reset of adaptation, resets the adaptation values to zero. This implies that the working points have
shifted to such an extent that a new adaptation learning process has to be triggered.

request. The adaptation values are set to the last stored adaptation value when an adaptation request active.

43.15.2.1.2.2.3.1.1.2.3 Adaptation of duty-cycle for VCV holding phase
The duty cycle adaptation (AD_PWM) is done ?rst since it decides the maximum current height that will be
achieved upon completion of adaptation. The adaptation for holding phase is as follows,
1. At every recurrence, the PWM adaptation value is increased by a calibratable value (C_PWM_INC_VCV_
CLOSE_SL_AD), until a particular pressure drop is breached in the rail when the fuel pressure difference in-
creases beyond the calibrated threshold (C_FUP_DIF_VCV_CLOSE_SL_AD_PWM).
This indicates that with the current adaptation value, the VCV cannot close and due to this, the delivery has
not happened and as a result we observe a pressure drop in the system.
2. On this breach, the last adapted value is decreased by a calibrated offset (C_PWM_OFS_VCV_CLOSE_SL_AD),
in order to ensure that the application of this adapted value closes the VCV before delivery.

3. Finally, the last adapted value (offset corrected) is applied for a few segments in order to ensure that the
system can accomidate the current arrived adaptation value without opening the VCV and causing a fuel
pressure drop again.
The switch to AD_T_DUR adaptation happens as soon as the SL adaptation counter increases beyond the
calibrated threshold (C_CTR_MAX_VCV_CLOSE_SL_AD_PWM).

43.15.2.1.2.2.3.1.1.2.4 Calculations of pull-in time for VCV peak phase
The duration adaptation (AD_T_DUR) is perfomed similar to the PWM adaptation. The adaptation for pull-in
phase is as follows,
1. At every recurrence, the duration adaptation value is increased by a calibratable value (C_T_DUR_INC_VCV_
CLOSE_SL_AD), until a particular pressure drop is breached in the rail when the fuel pressure difference in-
creases beyond the calibrated threshold (C_FUP_DIF_VCV_CLOSE_SL_AD_T_DUR).
This indicates that with the current adaptation value, the VCV cannot close and due to this, the delivery has
not happened and as a result we observe a pressure drop in the system.
2. On this breach, the SL counter is incremented and when it is equal to or increases beyond the calibrated
threshold (C_CTR_MAX_VCV_CLOSE_SL_AD_T_DUR), the last adapted value is decreased by a calibrated offset
(C_T_DUR_OFS_VCV_CLOSE_SL_AD), in order to ensure that the application of this adapted value closes the
VCV before delivery.
Finally, the last adapted value (offset corrected) is used as the pull-in time adaptation.
It is important to note that the counter calibration value for pull-in time is always and should always be cali-
brated atleast one value above the counter calibration for PWM in order to ensure that the adaptation prcoess
ends and the end of adaptation ?ag is raised (trigger for switching to AD_ON state) for application of the
adaptated values in the next VCV actuation cycle.

43.15.2.1.2.2.3.1.1.2.5 Calculations for adapted soft landing during VCV closing
After the end of adaptation the adaptation variables are corrected depending on the deviation of environmen-
tal conditions (working points) between their current values and their values at start of adaptation.
We know that the working points are stored at start of adaptation as R_VCV_CLOSE_SL_AD_ST and VB_VCV_
CLOSE_SL_AD_ST. In order to consider the effect of dynamic deviation of the working points during the process
of adaptation, the ?nal adaptation values (learnt from AD_PWM and AD_T_DUR states) are corrected based on
the current working point values (R_VCV and VB) through the below calibrations.
IP_PWM_VCV_CTL_SL_AD_END ? PWM adaptation correction based on working point status
IP_T_DUR_VCV_CTL_SL_AD_END ? T_DUR adaptation correction based on working point status
The calibration values of the above IP?s are based on the reference VCV values.

43.15.2.1.2.2.3.1.3.1 Calculation of duty-cycle for VCV holding phase
The duty cycle calculation for VCV holding phase for SL and normal operation is done in this section.
The hold phase duty cycle value (PWM_VCV_CTL_1) to be applied during non-SL or normal operating state is
given through PWM_VCV_CTL_0. But, PWM_VCV_CTL_0 corresponds to the pick-up phase during SL mode
where it is individually calculated in the subsystem CLC_PWM_VCV_CTL_2_OPM.
PWM_VCV_CTL_0 is set to zero in VCV_OPEN and MFP_START phases of the VCV.
During MFP_START phase, a long continuous pulse is applied to the VCV in order to have a continuous delivery
of fuel through the pump to enable a fast pressure build up in the rail. The calibration IP_PWM_VCV_CTL_
File: AE904B01.00D

FUSL, Fuel pressure actuator control
PULSE_ST is used to apply this long continuous duty cycle depending on battery voltage. This long continuous
pulse is also output through PWM_VCV_CTL_0, but only during start phase.
When the VCV SL adaptation phase is still in either STAT, AD_PWM or AD_T_DUR phase, then a basic value of
the duty cycle is applied through the calibration IP_PWM_VCV_CTL_2_BAS for the hold phase.
After the adaptation is completed (AD_ON), then the adapted value is corrected by a factor due to the effect
of dynamic change of adaptation working points, i.e. battery voltage and the VCV resistance. This factor is
realized through the calibration IP_FAC_COR_PWM_VCV_CTL_1. Finally, this factored adapted value is applied
for the PWM_VCV_CTL_1 calculation.
In case there is a wrong learning of the adaptation, then in order to have a minimum safety adaptation value
active all the time, a calibration constant is used, C_PWM_MAX_COR_VCV_CTL_1.

43.15.2.1.2.2.3.1.3.1.1 Duty cycle for VCV holding phase during normal states
The duty cycle calculation for the VCV holding phase can be split based on whether SL is active or not.

When SL is not active, then the duty cycle calculation for hold phase is calibrated based on the reference VCV,
the details are given below,

12053Project: VW SIMOS 18.1 EA888 Document key: 10213413 SPE 000 DE
Baseline: SC8L50Y0 Copyright Continental AG

Copyright �Continental AG. Transmittal, reproduction, dissemination and/or editing of this document as well as utilisation of its contents and communication thereof to others without
expressed authorisation are prohibited. Offenders will be held liable for payment of damages. All rights created by patent grant or registration of a utility model or design patent are reserved.
FUSL, Fuel pressure actuator control
IP_PWM_VCV_CTL_PULSE ? This is the basic map giving the PWM value dependent on battery voltage and
engine speed.
IP_FAC_CLOSE_RNG_PWM_VCV_CTL ? This is the map giving the factor affecting the PWM value due to the
affect of engine speed on the VCV closing angle. Since, we know that the duration for the duty cycle gets
affected by the engine speed, i.e. higher engine speed results in less duration of duty cycles application, since
the pump action is also faster.
IP_FAC_TFPA_PWM_VCV_CTL ? This is the map giving the factor affecting the PWM value due to the VCV coil
temperature dependency.
The below explanation gives the steps of duty cycle calculation during SL,
1. During STAT mode or AD_PWM mode, the basic reference VCV PWM values are taken from the calibration
depending on battery voltage and VCV resistance, IP_PWM_VCV_CTL_PULSE_SL. But, since during the process
of PWM adaptation, then adaptation value is increased at every recurrence, so, consequently the PWM duty
cycle value has to be decreased by subtracting the current adaptation value from the PWM value considered
from the map.
2. During AD_T_DUR mode or AD_ON mode, the already calculated PWM value during AD_PWM mode as
explained in step 1 above (PWM_VCV_CTL_0_MIN) is used as input to the calibration IP_PWM_VCV_CTL_PULSE_
SL_AD. This is an additional basic reference VCV calibration based on the PWM value learnt in the AD_PWM
mode. This addition to the already calculated value in AD_PWM mode is done in order to avoid a loss in the
total current height when the T_DUR adaptation is under progress.
3. During AD_ON mode, in addition to the calibration IP_PWM_VCV_CTL_PULSE_SL_AD value, the in?uence
of the movement of the working points during active SL application is considered. This is done through the
addition of,
(a). the difference of the PWM adaptation value at the current working point from the PWM adaptation value
of the VCV learnt at the start of adaptation.
(b). the calibratable offset value, C_PWM_OFS_VCV_CTL_PULSE_SL_AD. This offset is meant as a safety limit in
order to cover any insuf?cient working point in?uence left out from point (a) above.

43.15.2.1.2.2.3.1.3.2 Control angles and times for VCV actuation for type 1 VCV
This section consists of the control angle and time duration calculations for Bosch type VCV?s. Figure 56 shows
the control angles and time durations during normal operation and Figure 57 shows the control angles and
time durations during SL operation.
VCV_OPEN_ADD calculation :
The VCV_OPEN_ADD represents the total hold phase time of the actuation cycle.
During normal operation, it is calculated through the following calibrations,
IP_VCV_OPEN_ADD ? This is the basic reference VCV value for hold time in terms of crank angle. It depends on
the battery voltage and engine speed.
IP_FAC_CLOSE_RNG_VCV_OPEN_ADD ? This is the correction factor for the hold time based on the engine
speed and the angle at which the VCV should close. Higher the engine speed, less hold time available that can
be applied to the VCV and vice-versa.

IP_FAC_TFPA_VCV_OPEN_ADD ? This is the correction factor for the hold time based on the VCV coil tempera-
ture. Higher the coil temperature, higher the hold duration required and vice ? versa.
T_FUP_MIN_VCV_LOCK calculation :
In case the pressure developed inside the pump is lesser than a calibrated threshold C_FUP_MIN_LOCK_VCV
(usually around 20 bar), then the hydraulic pressure developed inside the pump chamber is not suf?cient in
aiding the closure of the VCV during the delivery stroke. So, in order to close the VCV during such situations,
a timer is used to hold the current of VCV for extended times and at an angle close to the TDC of the pump.
This allows the VCV to be closed through the current given to it, regardless of the low pressure in the pump
chamber. But, this extended current duration is also limited through a calibration C_T_MAX_FUP_MIN in order
to prevent the VCV from over heating.
T_DUR_VCV_CTL_FW calculation :
The free wheel time is calibrated through a constant, C_T_DUR_VCV_CTL_FW. This value is used in both normal
operation and during VCV closing SL operation. Free wheeling is deactive for VCV close SL when VCV open
SL is also active, in such cases, the free wheel time is set to zero.
ANG_CUR_OFF_VCV calculation :
The ANG_CUR_OFF_VCV represents the crank angle at which the current is switched off to the VCV coil.
This angle is referenced till the TDC of the pump is achieved. ANG_CUR_OFF_VCV is the duration in terms of
crank angle from the end of hold phase to the pump TDC.
When minimum delivery is requested through VCV_CLOSE_RNG, then the ANG_CUR_OFF_VCV is set to zero.
As long as low pressure delivery (lv_fup_min_lock) is active, then the extended current is ensured by giving the
minimum angle to the VCV through the calibration C_ANG_CUR_OFF_VCV_MIN.
When the low pressure delivery is inactive, then the ANG_COR_OFF_VCV is calculated through VCV_CLOSE_
RNG and VCV_OPEN_ADD.
When the VCV opening SL is active, then the ANG_CUR_OFF_VCV is calculated through a calibration dependant
on fuel pressure, IP_ANG_CUR_OFF_VCV_OPEN_SL.
An additional closing angle (ang_dly_ofs) calculation is done during SL operation. This additional angle is
essentially helpful when the VCV closing SL adaptation (AD_PWM or AD_T_DUR) is active, since the actual
closing of the VCV gets affected due to the changing adaptation values, threrefore to be safe that the VCV
closes surely, this additional closing angle is bene?cial and also, its useful in preventing debouncing effects of
VCV while closing when SL is active.
T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_ADD calculation :
The T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_ADD represents the total peak (or pull-in) time of the VCV actuation cycle.
Under normal operation, the VCV closes at end of T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_ADD.
During normal operation, it is calculated through the following calibrations,
IP_T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_ADD_3 ? This is the basic reference VCV value for peak time. It depends on the VCV
closing angle and engine speed.
IP_FAC_VB_T_DUR_VCV_CTL ? This is the correction factor for the peak time based on battery voltage. Lower
the battery voltage, higher is the peak time application to achieve the required current height.
IP_FAC_TFU_T_DUR_VCV_CTL ? This is the correction factor for the peak time based on the VCV coil tempera-
ture. Higher the coil temperature, higher the peak duration required and vice ? versa.
When minimum delivery is requested through VCV_CLOSE_RNG, then the peak time is set to a default mini-
mum value through the calibration C_T_PLS_DIAG_VCV. This is done so that the power stage diagnosis of the
VCV can be done even in case of minimum delivery.

This is the correction factor for the peak time based on the VCV coil tempera-
ture. Higher the coil temperature, higher the peak duration required and vice ? versa.
When minimum delivery is requested through VCV_CLOSE_RNG, then the peak time is set to a default mini-
mum value through the calibration C_T_PLS_DIAG_VCV. This is done so that the power stage diagnosis of the
VCV can be done even in case of minimum delivery.
During SL operation, it is calculated as explained below,
When the VCV closing SL state is either in STAT mode or in AD_PWM mode, then T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_ADD is
calculated through the calibration IP_T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_SL_PWM.

When the VCV closing SL state is in AD_T_DUR mode, then the T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_ADD is calculated through
the calibration IP_T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_SL_T_DUR.
It should be noted that the T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_ADD is only calculated in STAT, AD_PWM and AD_T_DUR phases
and is constant during AD_ON phase.
ANG_CUR_ON_VCV calculation :
The ANG_CUR_ON_VCV represents the crank angle starting from the point where the VCV has active current
in the coil upto the pump TDC. This angle is referenced till the TDC of the pump is achieved. It is the sum of
T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_ADD (converted to crank angle) and VCV_CLOSE_RNG.
The ANG_CUR_ON_VCV has to be greater than ANG_CUR_OFF_VCV by atleast one resolution, and this is the
reason why ANG_CUR_OFF_VCV is also considered in the calculation of ANG_CUR_ON_VCV.
T_DUR_VCV_CTL_PEAK calculation :
T_DUR_VCV_CTL_PEAK is the duration of the pull-in time or the peak current time during pull-in phase when
SL is active. During normal operation T_DUR_VCV_CTL_PEAK is equal to T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_ADD. The seperate
T_DUR_VCV_CTL_PEAK calculation is only active when the SL is active.
During the STAT mode or AD_PWM mode, a constant peak current is given through the calibration C_T_DUR_
VCV_CTL_PEAK_CLOSE_SL, in order to not have the peak current in?uence during PWM adaptation in AD_PWM
mode.
During AD_T_DUR mode, the peak current is calculated out of a calibration map, IP_T_DUR_VCV_CTL_PEAK_
CLOSE_SL. This map gives the peak current time to be applied depending on the last adaptated PWM value of
hold phase.
During AD_ON state, the peak time is based on the calibration map mentioned above and the adaptation
correction done after the T_DUR adaptation.
T_DUR_VCV_CTL_HOLD_0 calculation :
T_DUR_VCV_CTL_HOLD_0 is the time duration of the pick-up phase and is applied only when SL is active.
During STAT state and AD_ON state, additional time duration is calibrated through the constant, C_T_DLY_OFS_
VCV_CTL_AD_ON.
During AD_PWM state and AD_T_DUR state, additional time duration is calibrated through the constant, C_T_
DLY_OFS_VCV_CTL_AD_ACT.

43.15.2.1.2.2.3.1.3.3 Control angles and times for VCV actuation for type 2 VCV
The type 2 VCV refers to the Hitachi manufactured systems. The Hitachi valves actuation parameters are calcu-
lated differently compared to the Bosch systems. Also, they do not have SL feature and hence, no adaptation
and learning is needed.
During zero quantity delivery, in order to ensure minimum activation of the VCV for the power stage diagnosis,
a minimum calibration time is provided through C_T_PLS_DIAG_VCV.
T_DUR_VCV_CTL_PEAK calculation :
T_DUR_VCV_CTL_PEAK is the peak current duration during pull-in phase. It is calculated based on two calibra-
tion maps,
IP_T_DUR_VCV_CTL_BAS ? this is the base map dependant on battery voltage and engine speed.
IP_FAC_TFU_T_DUR_VCV_CTL ? this is the correction factor to the base map dependant on the VCV coil tem-
perature.
VCV_OPEN_ADD calculation :
VCV_OPEN_ADD is the total duration of active current phase of the VCV in terms of crank angle. It is also
calculated based on two calibration maps,
IP_T_VCV_OPEN_ADD ? this is the base map dependant on battery voltage and engine speed.
IP_FAC_TFPA_VCV_OPEN_ADD ? this is the correction factor to the base map dependant on the VCV coil tem-
perature.
T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_ADD calculation :
T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_ADD is the duration of current to be applied to the VCV until it closes. It is calculated based
on three calibration maps,
IP_T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_ADD_3 ? this is the base map dependant on engine speed and closing angle of VCV.
IP_T_DLY_VCV_VB_ADD ? this is the base map dependant on battery voltage.
IP_FAC_T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_ADD_VB ? this is the correction factor to the base map dependant on engine speed
and closing angle of VCV.
T_DUR_VCV_CTL_FW calculation :
The free wheel time is calibrated through a constant, C_T_DUR_VCV_CTL_FW.
ANG_CUR_ON_VCV calculation :
The ANG_CUR_ON_VCV represents the crank angle starting from the point where the VCV has active current
in the coil upto the pump TDC. This angle is referenced till the TDC of the pump is achieved. It is the addition
of T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_ADD (in terms of crank angle) and VCV_CLOSE_RNG (closing angle of VCV).
ANG_CUR_OFF_VCV calculation :
The ANG_CUR_OFF_VCV represents the crank angle at which the current is switched off to the VCV coil.
This angle is referenced till the TDC of the pump is achieved. ANG_CUR_OFF_VCV is the duration in terms of
crank angle from the end of hold phase to the pump TDC.
It is the difference of VCV_OPEN_ADD from ANG_CUR_ON_VCV.
If the timer T_FUP_MIN_VCV_LOCK is active, then the ANG_CUR_OFF_VCV is calibrated through the constant
C_ANG_CUR_OFF_VCV_MIN.
T_FUP_MIN_VCV_LOCK calculation :
In case the pressure developed inside the pump is lesser than a calibrated threshold C_FUP_MIN_LOCK_VCV
(usually around 20 bar), then the hydraulic pressure developed inside the pump chamber is not suf?cient in
aiding the closure of the VCV during the delivery stroke. So, in order to close the VCV during such situations,
a timer is used to keep the current of VCV for extended times and close to the TDC of the pump. This allows
the VCV to be closed through the current given to it, regardless of the low pressure in the pump chamber. But,
this extended current duration is also limited through a calibration C_T_MAX_FUP_MIN in order to prevent the
VCV from over heating.

Figure 43.15.73:
43.15.2.1.2.2.3.1.4.1 Deacceleration parameters for active soft landing during VCV opening
The main parameters for VCV opening SL are,
T_DEAC_OFF_VCV calculation :
Start of PWM duty cycle with reference to pump TDC is given through the base map IP_T_DEACC_OFF_VCV_
BAS which is dependant on the battery voltage and VCV resistance (coil temperature).
In case the VCV closing SL adaptation is ?nished, then an offset correction is done through the calibration map
IP_T_DEACC_OFF_VCV_AD_OFS based on the adaptation parameter of VCV closing SL and battery voltage at
start of VCV closing SL.
PWM_VCV_CTL_DEACC calculation :
PWM duty cycle value is given through the base map IP_PWM_VCV_CTL_DEACC_BAS which is dependant on
the battery voltage and VCV resistance (coil temperature).
In case the VCV closing SL adaptation is ?nished, then an offset correction is done through the calibration map
IP_PWM_VCV_CTL_DEACC_AD_OFS based on the adaptation parameter of VCV closing SL and battery voltage
at start of VCV closing SL.
T_DEAC_ON_VCV calculation :
PWM duty cycle application time for hold phase is given through the calibration constant C_T_DUR_VCV_
DEACC.
T_DUR_DEAC_VCV_FW calculation :
Free wheeling time is given through the calibration constant C_T_DUR_VCV_DEACC_FW.

43.15.2.1.2.2.3.2.1 Calculation of VCV current control parameters for currentless closed VCVs
The actuation and control parameters for currentless close VCV are given below.
ANG_CUR_ON_VCV calculation :
The ANG_CUR_ON_VCV represents the crank angle starting from the point where the VCV has active current
in the coil upto the pump TDC. This angle is referenced till the TDC of the pump is achieved. It is calculated
through the base calibration map IP_VCV_OPEN_ADD dependant on battery voltage and engine speed.
T_DUR_VCV_CTL_PEAK calculation :
T_DUR_VCV_CTL_PEAK is the peak current duration during pull-in phase. It is calculated through the base
calibration map IP_T_DUR_VCV_CTL_1 dependant on VCV closing angle and engine speed.
It has to be noted that the parameter T_DUR_VCV_CTL_HOLD_0 is not used for currentless close type VCV
since SL feature is not available.
T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_ADD calculation :
T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_ADD is the delay time between deactivation of VCV current feed and mechanical closing
of the VCV. So this is the duration of current NOT to be applied to the VCV until it closes. It is calculated
through the base calibration map IP_T_DLY_VCV_CLOSE_ADD_3 dependant on VCV closing angle and engine

FUSL, Fuel pressure actuator control
speed. The additional angle correction (ang_dly_vcv) is required to calculate the angle responding to T_DLY_
VCV_CLOSE_ADD, because current feed off event is set by ANG_CUR_OFF_VCV.
ANG_CUR_OFF_VCV calculation :
The ANG_CUR_OFF_VCV represents the crank angle at which the current is switched off to the VCV coil.
This angle is referenced till the TDC of the pump is achieved. ANG_CUR_OFF_VCV is the duration in terms of
crank angle from the end of hold phase to the pump TDC.
In case of zero delivery, the angle is set to zero. Under normal operation, it is calculated through the VCV
closing angle plus ang_dly_vcv or through the calibration map IP_VCV_OPEN_LIM_3 (dependant on battery
voltage and engine speed). This map is to ensure zero current at TDC for the next actuation cycle. If there is
residual inductivity at TDC due to the previous cycle, then the current in the next cycle gets affected and exact
opening angle of the VCV cannot be exactly determined.
T_DUR_VCV_CTL_FW calculation :
The free wheel time is calibrated through a constant, C_T_DUR_VCV_CTL_FW.
It has to be noted that the parameter low pressure timer T_FUP_MIN_VCV_LOCK is not used for currentless
close type VCV, since the default position of the VCV is to close, in case of zero current applied to it.
It has to be noted that the parameter VCV_OPEN_ADD is not used for currentless close type VCV.

43.15.2.1.2.2.3.2.1.1 Calculation of duty-cycle for VCV holding phase
It has to be noted that the parameters PWM_VCV_CTL_0 and PWM_VCV_CTL_1 are merged, since SL feature is
not available in currentless close type VCV.
When the VCV operating state is at MFP_MAX (maximum delivery) or at MFP_START (engine start phase)
with fuel pressure still below the setpoint, then maximum delivery mode is considered and no current feed is
applied. The VCV opens by suction created inside the pump chamber and closes due to the spring force.
After the fuel pressure has achieved the setpoint, then the delivery is restricted to avoid too high rail pressure
build up through the calibration, IP_PWM_VCV_CTL_PULSE_ST which is dependant on battery voltage.

FUSL, Fuel pressure actuator control
43.15.2.1.2.2.5.1 Action to Disable and Start
Switch to time based mode.
The VCV actuation is disabled when the PWM duty cycle value for hold phase is set to zero or when the VCV
stop request ?ag is active.
C_T_DUR_VCV_CTL_ST is the calibration constant through which the pull-in time for currentless closed type
VCV is given.
C_T_DUR_MAX is the calibration constant which gives the maximum pulse duration that can be applied at
once during any operation.
Every time there is an entry or exit from time based or segment based mode and vice-versa, then the VCV
stop request ?ag is reset. This is to ensure that the BSW is reset at every entry and exit of both modes, this
ensures there is no loss of actuation pulses during transition and to make the BSW robust.

43.15.2.1.3 Calculation Section for Actuator Test (Overview)
Start cycle is applied to the VCV when the actuator test is active.
The pull-in time is given through the calibration constant, C_T_DUR_VCV_CTL_ST. It is corrected by battery
voltage dependant correction through the calibration, IP_FAC_VB_T_DUR_VCV_CTL.
The maximum pulse duration that can be applied at once is given through the calibration constant, C_T_DUR_
MAX.
The free wheel time is given through the calibration constant, C_T_DUR_VCV_CTL_FW.

FUSL, Fuel supply system temperatures
Name Mode Coded Limits Display Limits Resolution Unit
TFPA temperature difference dependent to fuel ?ow heating effects
� General Information
This module describes all functionalities to estimate temperatures of components in the fuel supply system.
Following temperatures are determined:
- TFPA:
Coil temperature of fuel pressure actuator (for single piston high pressure pumps with ON-/OFF-valve for fuel
volume control). The temperature model for estimation of TFPA works with following physical principles / main
effects:
1.) Coil self heating due to heat origination caused by electric current feed of coil resistance.
2.) Heat dissipation from engine caused by mounting of high pressure fuel pump to engine block and air?ow
around fuel pressure actuator.
3.) Heat dissipation from fuel through the high pressure fuel pump caused by fuel ?ow from tank.
For every of these effects a temperature difference dependent to quantity and/or quality is calculated after the
principle of a heat exchanger. The quality is dependent to temperature difference between coil temperature
of fuel pressure actuator and environmental temperature (such as ambient, fuel temperature). The quantity is
dependent to intensity of mass throughput (such as engine speed, fuel volume ?ow through the high pressure
pump).

43.17.2.1.1 Calculation of temperature difference for electric coil heating
The temperature difference for electric coil heating (TFPA_EL) is dependent to number of actuation cycles
between two calculations of TFPA_EL. This number is represented by engine speed. The electrical effect allows
only heat dissipation into actuator coil, no electrical cooling effects are possible.
In case of current feed shut off, the temperature difference is set to zero. Current feed shut off detection
is realized by current actuation state of fuel pressure actuator dependent to used variant of high pressure
pump.

43.17.2.1.2 Calculation of temperature difference from engine heat dissipation
The temperature difference from engine heat dissipation is calculated with the effects of heat dissipation
caused by mounting between engine and high pressure pump and air?ow around fuel pressure actuator.
The temperature difference dependent to air?ow is calculated with temperature difference between ambient
and actuator temperature (quality information) and engine speed (quantity information).
Due to no real mass ?ow caused by heat dissipation from engine block, the temperature difference dependent
to engine heat?ow is calculated with temperature difference between coolant water (equals temperature of
engine block) and actuator temperature.

% Defueling function for low pressure fuel pump

IF LV_EFP

FUSL, Fuel research octane number statistical quanti?cation
The main issue of this function is to detect low gasoline octane, this is done with an request of calibratable
thresholds. The quanti?cation of the gasoline octane happened with the variable STATE_RON. This states and
state transits are described in ?gure 1. The state transit has following three modes, keep state, activate next
state or release current state.
The states are used in the module B0F2: Fuel research octane number diagnosis and there will be set the
corresponding errors.

43.20.6 State machine for Low octane (RON) Gasoline management
The logical values for reset and run the timer of gasoline octane RON index state detected is set to zero.
The delay counter for activation of low RON detection is set to an calibratibal value to be an function of the
engine speed, when the load dynamic function is active or the engine speed dynamic function is active or the
value of the spark retard till high MAP_DRV1 applied to engine is smaller than zero.
The state condition is set to "keep state", if the air mass is smaller than a index table without interpolation
dependent on the engine speed or the before described delay counter is not equal to zero.
LV_TMR_RST_RON_DET=0
LV_TMR_RUN_RON_DET=0
IF LV_MAF_TRA_KNK == 1

FUSL, Fuel pump low pressure diagnosis
This module contains the diagnostic of the low pressure Electrical Fuel Pump (EFP). The low pressure fuel
pump (EFP) delivers the required fuel pressure and mass fuel ?ow to the high pressure system (High pressure
pump, rail, injectors).
The diagnostic is done in several ways, in order to detect any malfunction that could endanger the correct
behaviour of the engine caused by EFP. On one side the regular electrical diagnosis is performed on the ATIC
that is driving the fuel pump command, on the other side the fuel pump electronic control unit is able to inform
the engine control unit(ECU) about faults related to fuel pump system, both the EFP command and diagnostic
are done by one single wire using one ECU pin.
Figure 43.22.1:
The diagnosis of the EFP consists of:
1.1 Con?guration of EFP parameters (variant coding)
In this section two EFP parameters are described :
- ERR_EFPPWM_FB_CONF: shows the EFP feedback con?guration (for 1 or 2 pumps connected, de-
pending on the engine con?guration)
- ACTION_INFR_SetFrqPwmEfp: selects the EFP operating frequency (20Hz or 100Hz)
The calculation of these parameters is done only at reset, this means that each time a change is
performed, the ECU should be powered down, at power up the results will be visible.
1.2. Hardware electrical diagnostic
In this section the function ACTION_INFR_GetElDiagEfp(CDN_DIAG_EFPPWM_BAS, ERR_DIAG_EFP-
PWM)is called, it returns the result of the electrical diagnostic made by the hardware of the ECU. The electronics
is able to return two diagnostic parameters:
- CDN_DIAG_EFPPWM_BAS (the condition to run the diagnostic)
- ERR_DIAG_EFPPWM (the result of the diagnostic: ?Short circuit to plus?, ?Short circuit to ground? and
?Open Load?).
1.3. Failure feedback recognition
One single wire is used for both pump command and diagnostic feedback like it can be seen on
the schematics, therefore we need to distinguish between diagnostic information and PWM signal
for EFP control. When a failure is detected by the EFP Control Module the command line will be
File: AEA01C01.00C
12142Project: VW SIMOS 18.1 EA888 Document key: 10213413 SPE 000 DE
Baseline: SC8L50Y0 Copyright Continental AG

expressed authorisation are prohibited. Offenders will be held liable for payment of damages. All rights created by patent grant or registration of a utility model or design patent are reserved.
FUSL, Fuel pump low pressure diagnosis
pulled to ground describing a de?ned pattern, in this way the ECU will know that the command
line will be used as diagnostic feedback information line. There are 3 possible states for the failure
feedback interpretation:
? no failure feedback recognized
? failure feedback possible
? failure feedback recognized
1.4. EFP diagnostic (PWM)
When no failure feedback recognition is possible and certain conditions are full-?lled (no inhibition
active, battery voltage above a threshold, EFPPWM between certain limits), the electrical diagnosis of the
PWM signal is done, the calculation of the corresponding diagnostic symptoms is based on the parameters
calculated in section 1.2: CDN_DIAG_EFPPWM_BAS, ERR_DIAG_EFPPWM.
1.5. Failure feedback diagnostic
If a failure is detected by the fuel pump control unit, a failure feedback is send to the ECU.
Depending on the pattern of the feedback signal the ECU is able to detect up to 8 different
failures.
The diagnostic of the feedback signal is performed only if there is no inhibition active
(LV_INH_ERR_EFPPWM_FB=0) and battery voltage is above a calibration threshold.
43.22.1 Determination of variant coding in?uence for electric fuel pump diagnosis
� General Information
(1)For the EFP control unit the variant of the EFP (STATE_VAR_EFP), is used to con?gure the failure feedback al-
gorithm by ERR_EFPPWM_FB_CONF:
? STATE_VAR_EFP = 00H or 01H (1 EFP connected to EFP control unit)->manual con?guration_1
? STATE_VAR_EFP = 02H or 03H (2 EFP connected to EFP control unit)->manual con?guration_2
(2)Additionally the EFP operating frequency is set in order to get the right PWM command signal(EFPPWM)
for the fuel pump that is used for the current engine variant. Depending on the value of a bit set by the variant
coding con?guration, two operating frequencies are supported:
- LV_VAR_EFPPWM_FRQ = 0 -> 20Hz
- LV_VAR_EFPPWM_FRQ = 1 ->100Hz
� Application Conditions
Initialisation: at reset:
If(1) STATE_VAR_EFP = 00H or 01H (1 EFP connected to EFP control
unit)

43.22.4 EFPPWM diagnosis
� General Information
The purpose is to diagnose the signal from the electronic driver, which controls the electrical fuel pump(EFP).
The input signal is a modulated control pulse (PWM).
The electronic driver(ATIC39) can distinguish between three symptoms: ?Short circuit to Vbatt?, ?Short circuit
to GND? and ?Open Load?. The diagnostic of all these symptoms is possible at the same time in the duty cycle
range [C_EFPPWM_DIAG_MIN ... C_EFPPWM_DIAG_MAX].
The error detection algorithm in this function for ?short circuit to GND? is respecting the status of the fail-
ure feedback recognition (ERR_EFPPWM_FB). The failure, detected by the hardware, is delivered by the basic
software(BSW) via ERR_DIAG_EFPPWM - the results are available when the function ACTION_INFR_GetEl-
DiagEfp(CDN_DIAG_EFPPWM_BAS, ERR_DIAG_EFPPWM) is called.
Error-symptoms: are de?ned to this diagnosis function as following (3 failures are supported)
 
> Short circuit to Vbatt (= SYM_0) 
> Short circuit to GND (= SYM_1) 
> Open load (= SYM_2) 
> - (= SYM_3)

� General Information
This module describes the electrical diagnosis of the fuel pressure sensor present in the low pressure system
and used for pressure regulation in the low pressure rail. It is very important to detect the presence of any
malfunction on this sensor because the pressure regulation depends exclusively on the feedback that we
get from the sensor, if the feedback is not valid then the pressure control will be not realistic and this might
endanger the correct behaviour of the engine itself.

The electrical diagnostic mechanism is based on the voltage that the sensor provides to the applicative soft-
ware(ASW), the acquisition of the voltage is done by the basic software(BSW) . There are 2 voltage thresholds
de?ned bellow: one is for Short circuit to battery voltage or to plus (SCP) and the other one is for Short circuit
to ground (SCG).
Short circuit to plus (ERR_SYM_ FUP_EFP = SYM_0):
If the voltage is exceeding the upper threshold(C_V_FUP_EFP_MV_MAX_DIAG) then we might have
a SCP, so the symptom is set (ERR_SYM_ FUP_EFP = 1) and the debouncing mechanism de?ned in ERRM
is start. If the symptom is present for a calibratable time, then the failure is con?rmed and the error ?ag is
set(LV_ERR_FUP_EFP= 1).
If V_FUP_EFP_MV > C_V_FUP_EFP_MV_MAX_DIAG
Then Symptom ?Short circuit in signal wire to VB or wire break? is
active, anti-bounce counter increment
ERR_SYM_ FUP_EFP = 1H
LV_ERR_FUP_EFP= 1 (after debounce)
Else Symptom ?Short circuit in signal wire to VB or wire break? is
inactive, anti-bounce counter decrement
ERR_SYM_FUP_EFP = 0H
LV_ERR_FUP_EFP = 0 (after debounce)
Endif
Short circuitto ground (ERR_SYM_ FUP_EFP = SYM_1):
If the voltage is bellow the lower threshold(C_V_FUP_EFP_MV_MIN_DIAG) then we might have aSCG,
so the symptom is set (ERR_SYM_ FUP_EFP = 2) and the debouncing mechanism de?ned in ERRM is start. If
the symptom is present for a calibratable time, then the failure is con?rmed and the error ?ag is set(LV_ERR_
FUP_EFP= 1).
If V_FUP_EFP_MV < C_V_FUP_EFP_MV_MIN_DIAG
then Symptom ?Short circuit in signal wire to ground? is active, anti-
bounce counter increment
ERR_SYM_ FUP = 2H
LV_ERR_FUP_EFP= 1 (after debounce)
else Symptom ?Short circuit in signal wire to ground? is inactive,
antibounce counter decrement
ERR_SYM_FUP_EFP = 0H
LV_ERR_FUP_EFP = 0 (after debounce)
Endif

Note : The anti-bounce is performed internally in the software, the calibrations related to anti-bounce for each

C_ABC_INC_XXX ? increment value of anti-bounce counter

XXX represents the respective diagnosis.
The fuel pressure damper is a mechanical device used in the low pressure line (at inlet side of the high pressure
pump) to dampen the pressure oscillations in the low pressure line before the entry of the fuel into the high
pressure pump. The fuel pressure damper diagnosis is performed in order to identify a defective damper. This
is done by detecting the presence of fuel pressure oscillations in the low pressure line which should have been
dampened by the damper.

The diagnosis is activated only if there is no inhibition. In case the diagnosis is active, the diagnostic condition
is always true.
The (low pressure side) fuel pressure analog input signal at the A/D-Input of the ECU is passed through a low
pass ?lter (Fig. 3), in which a calibratable ?lter factor (C_CRLC_FUP_EFP_DAMP_DET) is used, the output of the
?lter is treated as the damped value of the fuel pressure.

� Function Description
The diagnosis is active only if there is no inhibition. In case the diagnosis is active, the diagnostic condition is
always true.
The electrical diagnosis is capable of detecting two errors,
1. Short circuit in signal wire to Battery or wire break or open circuit (SCP/OC)
2. Short circuit in signal wire to Ground (SCG)
The analog voltage signal at the A/D-Input of the ECU is compared against calibratable voltage thresholds for
distinguishing b/w SCP and SCG errors.
43.27.1 Error detection :
Short circuit in signal wire to VB or wire break error :
If the fuel pressure sensor voltage exceeds a calibratable threshold (C_VP_FUP_MES_MAX_DIAG), then the SCP
symptom is triggered. The SCP error status is updated after anti-bounce ?ltering.
Short circuit in signal wire to ground :
If the fuel pressure sensor voltage is below a calibratable threshold (C_VP_FUP_MES_MIN_DIAG), then the SCG
symptom is triggered. The SCG error status is updated after anti-bounce ?ltering.

This particular diagnosis is performed in order to detect the electrical failures in the low side and high side

43.29.2 Diagnosis
� General Information
Since the VCV is driven with high side and low side switch, both diagnostic information are used to detect
short circuit and open circuit errors.
The symptoms of open circuit diagnosis short circuit diagnosis (SCG and SCP) of high side and low side
are clustered in one single error for each of the diagnosis, i.e. individual symptoms for OC, SCP and SCG
are calculated for both high side and low side separately, but the OC, SCG and SCP errors are set without
the distinction of being set through symptoms of high side or through symptoms of low side.
